Prim’s Algorithm

Prim’s Algorithm is a greedy algorithm used to find the Minimum Spanning Tree (MST) of a connected, weighted, undirected graph.

A Minimum Spanning Tree is a tree that:

connects all vertices

has no cycles

has the minimum possible total edge weight

How Prim’s Algorithm Works

Prim’s Algorithm starts from any one vertex and grows the MST step by step.

At each step:

choose the minimum weight edge

the edge must connect a visited vertex to an unvisited vertex

add that edge to the MST

repeat until all vertices are included

Steps of Prim’s Algorithm

Start with any vertex as the initial vertex.

Mark it as visited.

Find the minimum weight edge connecting a visited vertex to an unvisited vertex.

Add this edge to the MST.

Mark the new vertex as visited.

Repeat the process until V - 1 edges are added.

Example

Suppose the graph has vertices: A, B, C, D

Edges:

A-B = 1

A-C = 4

B-C = 2

B-D = 5

C-D = 3

Process

Start from A

Choose A-B (1)

Choose B-C (2)

Choose C-D (3)

MST Edges

A-B = 1

B-C = 2

C-D = 3

Total Cost

1 + 2 + 3 = 6

Time Complexity

Using adjacency matrix: O(V²)

Using priority queue and adjacency list: O(E log V)

Applications of Prim’s Algorithm

Network design

Road construction

Cable wiring

Water pipelines

Minimum cost connection problems

Important Points

Prim’s Algorithm works on connected, weighted, undirected graphs

It always selects the minimum edge

It is a greedy approach

The final result is a Minimum Spanning Tree

Conclusion

Prim’s Algorithm is an efficient method to find the Minimum Spanning Tree of a graph by selecting the smallest possible edge at each step without forming a cycle.